1
00:00:01,710 --> 00:00:03,837
DOCTOR: Get down!

2
00:00:05,297 --> 00:00:06,715
-Did they see you?
-I don't know.

3
00:00:06,798 --> 00:00:08,383
-But did they see you?
-I was too busy running!

4
00:00:08,467 --> 00:00:10,469
Martha, it's important,
did they see your face?

5
00:00:10,552 --> 00:00:13,263
-No, they couldn't have.
-Off we go.

6
00:00:16,433 --> 00:00:18,936
Ah! They're following us.

7
00:00:19,061 --> 00:00:20,771
How can they do that?
You've got a time machine.

8
00:00:20,854 --> 00:00:23,941
Stolen technology. They've got
a time agent's vortex manipulator.

9
00:00:24,024 --> 00:00:26,235
They can follow us wherever we go.

10
00:00:26,318 --> 00:00:29,613
Right across the universe.
They're never going to stop.

11
00:00:30,822 --> 00:00:33,283
Unless... I'll have to do it.

12
00:00:34,284 --> 00:00:36,161
-Martha, you trust me, don't you?
-Of course I do.

13
00:00:36,286 --> 00:00:39,331
-'Cause it all depends on you.
-What does? What am I supposed to do?

14
00:00:39,456 --> 00:00:41,917
Take this watch
because my life depends on it.

15
00:00:42,000 --> 00:00:44,378
This watch, Martha, this watch is...

16
00:00:58,725 --> 00:01:00,602
(KNOCK ON DOOR)

17
00:01:00,686 --> 00:01:02,396
Come in.

18
00:01:02,479 --> 00:01:05,399
Pardon me, Mr Smith, you're not
dressed yet. I can come back later.

19
00:01:05,482 --> 00:01:08,402
No, it's all right, it's all right,
put it down.

20
00:01:10,529 --> 00:01:12,072
I was...

21
00:01:14,825 --> 00:01:16,410
Sorry, sorry.

22
00:01:17,703 --> 00:01:20,497
Sometimes I have
these extraordinary dreams.

23
00:01:20,581 --> 00:01:23,125
-What about, sir?
-I dream I'm this...

24
00:01:24,251 --> 00:01:26,295
adventurer.

25
00:01:26,420 --> 00:01:28,755
This daredevil, a madman.

26
00:01:29,548 --> 00:01:31,592
"The Doctor”, I'm called.

27
00:01:31,675 --> 00:01:35,387
And last night,
I dreamt that you were there,

28
00:01:36,430 --> 00:01:39,474
as my...companion.

29
00:01:39,558 --> 00:01:42,728
A teacher and a housemaid, sir?
That's impossible.

30
00:01:42,853 --> 00:01:45,314
I'm a man from another world, you know.

31
00:01:45,397 --> 00:01:48,191
Well, then it can't be true
'cause there's no such thing.

32
00:01:48,275 --> 00:01:51,028
This thing, the watch...

33
00:01:56,241 --> 00:01:58,160
It's funny how dreams slip away.

34
00:01:58,243 --> 00:02:00,162
But I do remember one thing.

35
00:02:00,245 --> 00:02:02,456
It all took place in the future.

36
00:02:03,248 --> 00:02:05,959
In the year of our Lord, 2007.

37
00:02:06,043 --> 00:02:07,878
I can prove that wrong for you, sir.

38
00:02:08,045 --> 00:02:10,088
Here's the morning paper.

39
00:02:10,172 --> 00:02:14,343
It's Monday November 10, 1913,
and you're completely human, sir.

40
00:02:15,552 --> 00:02:18,305
-As human as they come.
-Mmm. That's me.

41
00:02:19,806 --> 00:02:21,850
Completely human.

42
00:02:26,063 --> 00:02:29,066
(DOCTOR WHO THEME)

43
00:03:24,204 --> 00:03:25,789
Good morning, sir.

44
00:03:28,375 --> 00:03:29,918
Good morning, sir.

45
00:03:36,299 --> 00:03:37,634
Headmaster.

46
00:03:42,305 --> 00:03:44,266
"The French were all but spent,

47
00:03:44,349 --> 00:03:47,102
"with only two battalions
of the old guard remaining.

48
00:03:47,185 --> 00:03:51,148
"The final reserve force
was charged with protecting Napoleon.

49
00:03:51,690 --> 00:03:54,401
"But by evening,
the advance of the allied troops

50
00:03:54,484 --> 00:03:57,195
"had forced them to retreat."”

51
00:04:04,578 --> 00:04:06,496
Morning, sir.

52
00:04:06,621 --> 00:04:07,956
Yes, hi.

53
00:04:10,876 --> 00:04:15,714
Head in the clouds, that one.
I don't know why you're so sweet on him.

54
00:04:15,922 --> 00:04:17,758
He's just kind to me, that's all.

55
00:04:17,841 --> 00:04:20,093
Not everyone's that considerate,
what with me being...

56
00:04:20,177 --> 00:04:23,430
-A Londoner?
-Exactly. Good old London town!

57
00:04:23,513 --> 00:04:24,723
(BOTH LAUGHING)

58
00:04:24,848 --> 00:04:26,600
Now then, you two.

59
00:04:26,767 --> 00:04:30,562
You're not paid to have fun, are you?
Put a little backbone into it.

60
00:04:30,645 --> 00:04:34,149
-Yes, sir. Sorry, sir.
-You there. What's your name again?

61
00:04:34,232 --> 00:04:35,901
Martha, sir. Martha Jones.

62
00:04:36,067 --> 00:04:37,652
Well, tell me then, Jones,

63
00:04:37,736 --> 00:04:41,698
with hands like those,
how can you tell when something's clean?

64
00:04:41,865 --> 00:04:43,992
(LAUGHING)

65
00:04:44,075 --> 00:04:47,662
-That's very funny, sir.
-Careful now, don't tense about it.

66
00:04:47,746 --> 00:04:50,290
I'd like to smack my bucket
over his head.

67
00:04:50,373 --> 00:04:52,334
Oh, I wish!

68
00:04:53,710 --> 00:04:55,796
Just think, though.

69
00:04:55,879 --> 00:04:59,716
In a few years' time, boys like that
will be running the country.

70
00:04:59,800 --> 00:05:01,218
1913.

71
00:05:02,135 --> 00:05:04,054
They might not.

72
00:05:05,972 --> 00:05:08,350
-Excuse me, ma'am.
-Oh, good morning, Mr Smith.

73
00:05:08,433 --> 00:05:10,393
Oh! Here we go.

74
00:05:10,894 --> 00:05:13,396
-Let me help you.
-No, no, I've got it, no.

75
00:05:14,648 --> 00:05:18,819
Er... Just to retrieve...
So, if you could take these...

76
00:05:18,902 --> 00:05:20,445
Thank you.

77
00:05:20,529 --> 00:05:22,322
-There we are.
-Good.

78
00:05:22,405 --> 00:05:23,615
No harm done.

79
00:05:23,698 --> 00:05:26,576
-So, how was Jenkins?
-Oh, just a cold, nothing serious.

80
00:05:26,660 --> 00:05:28,119
I think he's missing his mother
more than anything.

81
00:05:28,245 --> 00:05:29,412
Ah, can't have that.

82
00:05:29,538 --> 00:05:31,790
He received a letter this morning,
so he's a lot more chipper.

83
00:05:31,873 --> 00:05:35,836
-I appear to be holding your books.
-Yes, so you are, sorry. Sorry.

84
00:05:35,919 --> 00:05:39,172
-Yes, just let me...
-No, why don't I take half?

85
00:05:39,256 --> 00:05:42,592
Brilliant idea. Brilliant. Perfect.
Division of lab our.

86
00:05:42,717 --> 00:05:45,595
-We make quite a team.
-Don't we just?

87
00:05:46,388 --> 00:05:50,016
So these books, were they being taken
in any particular direction?

88
00:05:50,100 --> 00:05:53,478
Yes, um, this way.

89
00:05:55,480 --> 00:05:58,066
I always say, Matron, you give the boys
a good head of steam,

90
00:05:58,149 --> 00:06:00,527
they'll soon wear themselves out.

91
00:06:00,610 --> 00:06:02,487
Truth be told,
when it's just you and me,

92
00:06:02,612 --> 00:06:04,865
I'd much rather
you call me Nurse Redfern.

93
00:06:04,948 --> 00:06:07,200
Matron sounds rather, well, matronly.

94
00:06:07,284 --> 00:06:09,828
Ah! Nurse Redfern it is, then.

95
00:06:10,036 --> 00:06:13,248
Though we've known each other all of
two months, you could even say Joan.

96
00:06:13,331 --> 00:06:14,916
-Joan?
-That's my name.

97
00:06:15,000 --> 00:06:16,251
Well, obviously.

98
00:06:16,334 --> 00:06:18,378
-And it's John, isn't it?
-Yes, it is, yes.

99
00:06:18,461 --> 00:06:21,715
Have you seen this, John? The annual
dance at the village hall tomorrow?

100
00:06:21,798 --> 00:06:24,718
It's nothing formal,
but rather fun by all accounts.

101
00:06:24,801 --> 00:06:26,636
Do you think you'll go?

102
00:06:28,138 --> 00:06:29,723
I hadn't thought about it.

103
00:06:29,806 --> 00:06:33,685
It's been ages since I've been
to a dance, only no one's asked me.

104
00:06:35,312 --> 00:06:38,148
Well, I should imagine that you'd be...

105
00:06:38,231 --> 00:06:41,484
I mean... I mean,
I never thought you'd be one for...

106
00:06:41,568 --> 00:06:44,029
There's no reason why you shouldn't,
if you do, you may not...

107
00:06:44,154 --> 00:06:46,156
I probably won't,
but even if I did, then I...

108
00:06:46,281 --> 00:06:49,326
-I couldn't, um... I wouldn't want to...
-The stairs.

109
00:06:49,409 --> 00:06:51,953
-What about the stairs?
-They're right behind you.

110
00:06:54,789 --> 00:06:55,832
(GROANS)

111
00:06:55,957 --> 00:06:58,668
Stop it. I get boys
causing less fuss than this.

112
00:06:58,793 --> 00:06:59,961
But it hurts.

113
00:07:00,045 --> 00:07:02,339
-Is he all right?
-Excuse me, Martha.

114
00:07:02,464 --> 00:07:04,925
It's hardly good form to enter
a master's study without knocking.

115
00:07:05,008 --> 00:07:07,177
Sorry. You're right, yeah.

116
00:07:08,970 --> 00:07:12,015
But is he all right?
They said you fell down the stairs, sir.

117
00:07:12,098 --> 00:07:14,392
It was just a tumble, that's all.

118
00:07:14,476 --> 00:07:16,478
-Have you checked for concussion?
-I have.

119
00:07:16,561 --> 00:07:19,898
And I dare say
I know a lot more about it than you.

120
00:07:20,607 --> 00:07:24,069
Sorry. I'll just tidy your things.

121
00:07:25,820 --> 00:07:28,657
I was just telling
Nurse Redfern, Matron,

122
00:07:28,740 --> 00:07:32,202
about my dreams.
They are quite remarkable tales.

123
00:07:33,203 --> 00:07:37,290
I keep imagining that I'm someone else
and that I'm hiding.

124
00:07:37,374 --> 00:07:39,250
Hiding. In what way?

125
00:07:39,584 --> 00:07:40,919
Erm...

126
00:07:41,044 --> 00:07:43,546
They're almost every night and...

127
00:07:43,630 --> 00:07:46,049
-This is going to sound silly.
-Tell me.

128
00:07:46,716 --> 00:07:49,386
I dream, quite often, that...

129
00:07:50,220 --> 00:07:51,972
That I have two hearts.

130
00:07:52,055 --> 00:07:55,225
Well then, I can be the judge of that.
Let's find out.

131
00:08:04,484 --> 00:08:06,069
(HEART BEATING)

132
00:08:10,073 --> 00:08:13,827
I can confirm the diagnosis.
Just one heart. Singular.

133
00:08:15,662 --> 00:08:17,414
I have, um, I have written down

134
00:08:17,497 --> 00:08:20,500
some of these dreams
in the form of fiction.

135
00:08:21,543 --> 00:08:24,004
-Not that it would be of any interest.
-I'd be very interested.

136
00:08:24,087 --> 00:08:26,631
Yeah? Well...

137
00:08:28,758 --> 00:08:31,928
Never actually
shown it to anyone before.

138
00:08:34,305 --> 00:08:36,933
"A Journal of Impossible Things."

139
00:08:43,565 --> 00:08:46,151
Look at these creatures.
Such imagination.

140
00:08:46,276 --> 00:08:48,903
-Oh. It's become quite a hobby.
-Oh.

141
00:08:55,785 --> 00:08:57,620
It's wonderful.

142
00:08:58,246 --> 00:09:00,498
You have quite an eye
for the pretty girls.

143
00:09:00,582 --> 00:09:05,295
Oh, no, no, she's just an invention.
This character Rose. I call her Rose.

144
00:09:06,504 --> 00:09:08,631
Seems to disappear later on.

145
00:09:14,012 --> 00:09:17,140
Oh, that's the box, the blue box.
It's always there.

146
00:09:17,307 --> 00:09:20,060
Like a magic carpet...

147
00:09:20,143 --> 00:09:23,772
This fun little box that transports me
to faraway places.

148
00:09:23,855 --> 00:09:25,732
-Like a doorway?
-Mmm.

149
00:09:26,983 --> 00:09:28,860
I sometimes think

150
00:09:28,943 --> 00:09:31,863
how magical life would be
if stories like this were true.

151
00:09:31,988 --> 00:09:33,448
JOAN: If only.

152
00:09:34,407 --> 00:09:37,035
It's just a dream.

153
00:09:42,123 --> 00:09:43,374
Ma'am.

154
00:09:44,292 --> 00:09:46,419
-That book.
-Oh, I'll look after it, don't worry.

155
00:09:46,503 --> 00:09:49,881
-He did say I could read it.
-But it's silly, that's all.

156
00:09:50,673 --> 00:09:52,926
Just stories.

157
00:09:53,009 --> 00:09:55,720
-Who is he, Martha?
-I'm sorry?

158
00:09:55,804 --> 00:09:59,140
It's like he's left the kettle on,
like he knows he has something

159
00:09:59,224 --> 00:10:01,768
to get back to,
but he can't remember what.

160
00:10:01,851 --> 00:10:04,354
-It's just him.
-You arrived with him, didn't you?

161
00:10:04,479 --> 00:10:06,815
He found you employment here
at the school, isn't that right?

162
00:10:06,898 --> 00:10:10,360
I used to work for the family.
He just sort of inherited me.

163
00:10:10,443 --> 00:10:13,196
Well, I'd be careful.
If you don't mind my saying,

164
00:10:13,321 --> 00:10:15,532
you sometimes seem
a little familiar with him.

165
00:10:15,615 --> 00:10:17,867
Best remember your position.

166
00:10:18,868 --> 00:10:20,870
Yes, ma'am.

167
00:10:22,580 --> 00:10:25,083
Ah, Latimer, here you are.

168
00:10:25,166 --> 00:10:26,960
Latin translation.

169
00:10:27,043 --> 00:10:29,629
Blasted Catullus.
I want it done by morning.

170
00:10:29,712 --> 00:10:31,798
-Yes, sir.
-And no mistakes.

171
00:10:31,881 --> 00:10:34,509
I want it written
in my best handwriting.

172
00:10:34,592 --> 00:10:38,555
Listen, Father says he's been promoted.
That means more money.

173
00:10:38,680 --> 00:10:42,225
-Might end up in a better school.
-Ah, you should enjoy it, sir.

174
00:10:42,308 --> 00:10:45,228
My uncle had a six-month posting
in Johannesburg.

175
00:10:45,311 --> 00:10:47,939
Says it was the most beautiful
countryside on God's earth.

176
00:10:48,022 --> 00:10:50,358
-What are you talking about?
-Africa.

177
00:10:50,441 --> 00:10:52,402
-Your father.
-Have you been reading my post?

178
00:10:52,527 --> 00:10:54,487
-What?
-Who said Africa?

179
00:10:55,363 --> 00:10:57,907
I've only just read the word myself.

180
00:10:58,032 --> 00:11:00,535
-How did you know that?
-I haven't...

181
00:11:00,618 --> 00:11:04,038
-Have you been spying on me?
-No. I just guessed.

182
00:11:04,122 --> 00:11:08,501
-What's that supposed to mean?
-I'm good at guessing, that's all.

183
00:11:08,585 --> 00:11:10,044
Idiot.

184
00:11:14,757 --> 00:11:18,011
Sometimes I say things
and they turn out to be correct.

185
00:11:18,094 --> 00:11:22,390
Just little things. Tiny things.
I can't help it.

186
00:11:23,850 --> 00:11:25,935
It's just some sort of luck.

187
00:11:27,729 --> 00:11:30,315
Right. Well, never mind
that little toad. Who's for beer?

188
00:11:30,398 --> 00:11:31,608
You've got beer?

189
00:11:31,691 --> 00:11:34,694
No, but Baxter's hidden a secret supply
in Blackdown Woods.

190
00:11:34,777 --> 00:11:36,946
Well, what are you waiting for?

191
00:11:37,030 --> 00:11:39,866
Make sure the bursar's down the pub
before you go past his window.

192
00:11:39,949 --> 00:11:43,244
-A bottle for everyone, is it?
-And none for the filth.

193
00:11:43,995 --> 00:11:46,289
And hurry back, Baines. I'm parched.

194
00:11:49,667 --> 00:11:53,171
Ooh, it's freezing out here. Why can't
we have a drink inside the pub?

195
00:11:53,254 --> 00:11:55,965
Don't be ridiculous.
You do get these notions.

196
00:11:56,090 --> 00:11:59,886
It's all very well those suffragettes,
but that's London. That's miles away.

197
00:11:59,969 --> 00:12:02,722
Don't you want to scream sometimes,
having to bow and scrape and behave?

198
00:12:02,805 --> 00:12:05,225
-Don't you just want to tell them?
-I don't know.

199
00:12:05,308 --> 00:12:07,227
Things must be different
in your country.

200
00:12:07,310 --> 00:12:09,729
Well, they are.
Thank God I'm not staying here.

201
00:12:09,812 --> 00:12:11,314
You keep saying that.

202
00:12:11,439 --> 00:12:15,401
Just you wait. One more month
and I'm as free as the wind.

203
00:12:15,485 --> 00:12:17,737
Wish you could come with me, Jenny.
You'd love it.

204
00:12:17,820 --> 00:12:20,198
-Where you gonna go?
-Anywhere.

205
00:12:20,281 --> 00:12:22,033
Just look up there.

206
00:12:22,659 --> 00:12:25,828
Imagine you could go all the way
out to the stars.

207
00:12:26,704 --> 00:12:28,915
You don't half say mad things.

208
00:12:29,123 --> 00:12:32,710
That's where I'm going.
Into the sky, all the way out.

209
00:12:33,461 --> 00:12:34,754
Hmm!

210
00:12:37,632 --> 00:12:39,342
Did you see that?

211
00:12:39,425 --> 00:12:41,594
-See what?
-Did you see it, though?

212
00:12:41,678 --> 00:12:43,846
Right up there, just for a second.

213
00:12:43,972 --> 00:12:45,932
Martha, there's nothing there.

214
00:13:27,515 --> 00:13:30,184
Matron, are you all right?

215
00:13:30,268 --> 00:13:32,812
Did you see that?
There was something in the woods.

216
00:13:32,895 --> 00:13:35,148
-This light.
-Anything wrong, ladies?

217
00:13:35,231 --> 00:13:37,233
Far too cold
to be standing round in the dark.

218
00:13:37,317 --> 00:13:40,194
JOAN: There. There. Look, in the sky.

219
00:13:40,278 --> 00:13:42,739
Oh, that's beautiful.

220
00:13:43,781 --> 00:13:47,785
All gone. Commonly known as a meteorite.

221
00:13:48,411 --> 00:13:51,831
It's just rocks falling to the ground,
that's all.

222
00:13:51,914 --> 00:13:53,166
Came down in the woods.

223
00:13:53,249 --> 00:13:56,961
No, no, they always look close,
but actually they're miles off.

224
00:13:57,045 --> 00:13:59,672
Nothing left but a cinder.

225
00:13:59,756 --> 00:14:03,217
Now, I should escort you
back to the school.

226
00:14:03,301 --> 00:14:05,845
-Ladies?
-No, we're fine, thanks.

227
00:14:05,928 --> 00:14:08,056
Then I shall bid you good night.

228
00:14:10,058 --> 00:14:12,101
Jenny, where was that?

229
00:14:12,185 --> 00:14:14,145
On the horizon,
where the light was headed.

230
00:14:14,228 --> 00:14:16,773
That's by Coopers Field.

231
00:14:16,856 --> 00:14:20,526
You can't just run off! It's dark.
You'll break a leg!

232
00:15:03,111 --> 00:15:04,821
I say, hello?

233
00:15:07,824 --> 00:15:09,909
Some kind of aeroplane?

234
00:15:12,161 --> 00:15:13,996
You chaps all right?

235
00:15:30,513 --> 00:15:33,766
What? That's... That's impossible.

236
00:15:47,947 --> 00:15:49,699
Some kind of door.

237
00:15:51,742 --> 00:15:53,619
(ECHOING) Hello?

238
00:15:55,788 --> 00:15:57,707
Is there anyone there?

239
00:16:11,929 --> 00:16:16,142
There you are.
Nothing there. I told you so.

240
00:16:16,225 --> 00:16:17,935
And that's Coopers Field?

241
00:16:18,019 --> 00:16:20,980
As far as the eye can see,
and no falling star.

242
00:16:21,063 --> 00:16:23,774
Now, come on, I'm frozen to the bone.
Let's go.

243
00:16:23,858 --> 00:16:26,736
As your Mr Smith says, "Nothing to see.”

244
00:16:34,577 --> 00:16:37,497
But I don't understand. Who are you?

245
00:16:37,580 --> 00:16:39,499
MALE VOICE: We are the Family.

246
00:16:39,582 --> 00:16:43,503
FEMALE VOICE: Far more important,
who are you, little thing?

247
00:16:43,586 --> 00:16:48,257
My name's Baines. Jeremy Baines.
Please, can I go?

248
00:16:48,382 --> 00:16:51,677
FEMALE VOICE: I'm so sorry, Baines,
Jeremy Baines,

249
00:16:51,761 --> 00:16:55,014
but I don't think you can ever leave.

250
00:16:55,097 --> 00:16:59,393
But who are you? Why can't I see you?

251
00:16:59,477 --> 00:17:01,938
MALE VOICE. Why would you want
to see us?

252
00:17:03,272 --> 00:17:05,024
I want to know what you look like.

253
00:17:05,107 --> 00:17:07,735
FEMALE VOICE: Oh, that's easily answered

254
00:17:07,818 --> 00:17:11,864
because very soon,
we will look so familiar.

255
00:17:16,744 --> 00:17:20,122
Where is he? Promises a beer
and then vanishes into the night.

256
00:17:23,167 --> 00:17:25,628
There he is. Let him in.

257
00:17:37,557 --> 00:17:41,394
Well, Baines, you dolt. Thought you'd
been caught by the rozzers.

258
00:17:43,688 --> 00:17:44,981
Well, then?

259
00:17:45,064 --> 00:17:47,358
Where is it, man?
Where's the blessed beer?

260
00:17:47,441 --> 00:17:50,027
There was no beer. It was gone.

261
00:17:50,111 --> 00:17:52,280
Damn it all, I've been waiting.

262
00:17:52,363 --> 00:17:54,865
Pretty poor show, Baines, I have to say.

263
00:17:55,491 --> 00:17:56,951
(SNIFFS)

264
00:17:57,034 --> 00:17:59,287
What's the matter with you?
Caught the sniffles out there?

265
00:17:59,370 --> 00:18:02,206
Yes, I must have. It was cold.

266
00:18:03,249 --> 00:18:04,834
Very cold.

267
00:18:06,919 --> 00:18:09,589
Well, don't spread it about.
I don't want your germs.

268
00:18:09,672 --> 00:18:11,882
Come on, might as well get some sleep.

269
00:18:11,966 --> 00:18:16,178
Come on, chaps, maybe tomorrow.
Jackson's got some beer in the pavilion.

270
00:19:07,980 --> 00:19:09,565
Hello.

271
00:19:11,525 --> 00:19:13,402
Talking to a machine.

272
00:19:30,836 --> 00:19:32,463
DOCTOR: Get down!

273
00:19:43,766 --> 00:19:46,060
Ah! They're following us.

274
00:19:46,143 --> 00:19:48,312
They can follow us wherever we go.

275
00:19:48,396 --> 00:19:51,440
Right across the universe.
They're never gonna stop.

276
00:19:52,233 --> 00:19:54,443
-Martha, you trust me, don't you?
-Of course I do.

277
00:19:54,527 --> 00:19:56,779
'Cause it all depends on you.

278
00:20:01,659 --> 00:20:05,287
Martha, this watch is me.

279
00:20:05,830 --> 00:20:07,373
Right, okay, gotcha.

280
00:20:07,456 --> 00:20:10,126
No! Hold on! Completely lost.

281
00:20:10,209 --> 00:20:12,044
Those creatures are hunters.
They can sniff out anyone.

282
00:20:12,128 --> 00:20:14,213
And me being a Time Lord,
well, I'm unique.

283
00:20:14,296 --> 00:20:16,632
They can track me down across
the whole of time and space.

284
00:20:16,716 --> 00:20:18,592
Huh. And the good news is?

285
00:20:18,676 --> 00:20:20,803
They can smell me, they haven't seen me,

286
00:20:20,886 --> 00:20:23,472
and their life supplies are running out,
so we hide.

287
00:20:23,639 --> 00:20:26,892
-Wait for them to die.
-But they can track us down.

288
00:20:26,976 --> 00:20:29,353
That's why I've got to do it.

289
00:20:29,478 --> 00:20:31,981
I have to stop being a Time Lord.

290
00:20:32,690 --> 00:20:34,358
I'm gonna become human.

291
00:20:48,080 --> 00:20:50,249
Never thought I'd use this.

292
00:20:51,167 --> 00:20:53,586
All the times I've wondered.

293
00:20:53,669 --> 00:20:56,672
-What does it do?
-Chameleon Arch.

294
00:20:56,756 --> 00:20:58,591
Rewrites my biology.

295
00:20:58,674 --> 00:21:01,969
It literally changes every single cell
in my body. I've set it to human.

296
00:21:02,052 --> 00:21:03,763
The Tardis will take care of everything.

297
00:21:03,846 --> 00:21:06,265
Invent a life story for me,
find me a setting and integrate.

298
00:21:06,348 --> 00:21:09,018
It can't do the same for you.
You'll just have to improvise.

299
00:21:09,143 --> 00:21:11,520
I should have just enough
residual awareness to let you in.

300
00:21:11,604 --> 00:21:15,816
Hold on, if you're going to rewrite
every cell, isn't it going to hurt?

301
00:21:15,900 --> 00:21:18,402
Oh, yeah. It'll hurt.

302
00:21:43,219 --> 00:21:45,095
Is this working?

303
00:21:45,221 --> 00:21:47,014
Martha, before I change,

304
00:21:47,097 --> 00:21:49,391
here's a list of instructions
for when I'm human.

305
00:21:49,475 --> 00:21:51,602
One, don't let me hurt anyone.

306
00:21:51,727 --> 00:21:53,646
We can't have that, but you know what
humans are like.

307
00:21:53,729 --> 00:21:55,731
Two, don't worry about the Tardis.

308
00:21:55,815 --> 00:21:59,109
I'll put it on emergency power so they
can't detect it. Just let it hide away.

309
00:21:59,193 --> 00:22:01,153
Four... No.

310
00:22:01,237 --> 00:22:05,074
Wait a minute. Three, no getting
involved in big historical events.

311
00:22:05,157 --> 00:22:08,244
Four, you. Don't let me abandon you.

312
00:22:09,203 --> 00:22:10,704
And five...

313
00:22:12,373 --> 00:22:16,544
But there was a meteor, a shooting
star, what am I supposed to do then?

314
00:22:16,627 --> 00:22:19,839
And 23, if anything goes wrong,

315
00:22:19,922 --> 00:22:22,675
if they find us, Martha,
then you know what to do.

316
00:22:22,758 --> 00:22:24,677
Open the watch.

317
00:22:24,760 --> 00:22:27,096
Everything I am is kept safe in there.

318
00:22:27,179 --> 00:22:30,391
I've put a perception filter on it so
the human me won't think anything of it.

319
00:22:30,474 --> 00:22:35,062
To him, it's just a watch.
But don't open it unless you have to.

320
00:22:35,145 --> 00:22:39,191
"Cause once it's open,
then the Family will be able to find me.

321
00:22:39,275 --> 00:22:42,403
It's all down to you, Martha.
Your choice.

322
00:22:44,238 --> 00:22:46,782
Oh! And thank you.

323
00:22:50,703 --> 00:22:53,122
I wish you'd come back.

324
00:22:53,914 --> 00:22:54,123
(KNOCKING)

325
00:22:54,123 --> 00:22:55,082
(KNOCKING)

326
00:22:57,084 --> 00:22:59,336
You told me to come
and collect that book, sir.

327
00:22:59,420 --> 00:23:01,046
Good lad, yes, yes!

328
00:23:02,047 --> 00:23:04,550
The Definitive Account of Mafeking
by Aitchinson Price.

329
00:23:04,633 --> 00:23:06,135
Where did I put it?

330
00:23:06,260 --> 00:23:10,014
And I wanted a little word.
Your marks aren't quite good enough.

331
00:23:10,097 --> 00:23:12,016
I'm top 10 in my class, sir.

332
00:23:12,141 --> 00:23:15,728
Now, be honest, Timothy.
You should be the very top.

333
00:23:15,811 --> 00:23:18,147
You're a clever boy.
You seem to be hiding it.

334
00:23:18,230 --> 00:23:20,065
Where is that book?

335
00:23:20,149 --> 00:23:24,987
And I know why. Keeping your head low
avoids the mockery of your classmates.

336
00:23:25,779 --> 00:23:28,324
But no man should hide himself,
don't you think?

337
00:23:28,449 --> 00:23:30,492
-Yes, sir.
-You're clever.

338
00:23:30,618 --> 00:23:32,286
FEMALE VOICE: Time Lord.

339
00:23:32,369 --> 00:23:34,496
You should be proud of it. Use it.

340
00:23:34,580 --> 00:23:36,165
(WHISPERING VOICES)

341
00:23:36,248 --> 00:23:38,125
Time Lord.

342
00:23:38,417 --> 00:23:41,420
FEMALE VOICE: Timothy, hide us.

343
00:23:41,503 --> 00:23:45,466
DOCTOR: The secret lies within.
I'm trapped. I'm caged.

344
00:23:45,549 --> 00:23:48,218
Inside the cold, in the dark, waiting.

345
00:23:48,302 --> 00:23:52,097
FEMALE VOICE: Reach out, boy. Reach out.
DOCTOR: Always waiting.

346
00:23:52,640 --> 00:23:55,267
Fascinating details about the siege,
really quite remarkable.

347
00:23:55,351 --> 00:23:58,312
-Are you all right?
-Yes, sir. Fine, sir.

348
00:23:58,395 --> 00:24:00,439
Right, then. Good.

349
00:24:00,522 --> 00:24:02,942
And remember, use that brain of yours.

350
00:24:03,025 --> 00:24:05,402
The power of a Time Lord.

351
00:24:08,030 --> 00:24:11,575
You're really not looking yourself,
old chap. Anything bothering you?

352
00:24:11,700 --> 00:24:14,203
No, sir. Thank you, sir.

353
00:24:34,223 --> 00:24:37,309
DOCTOR: You are not alone.
Keep me hidden.

354
00:24:37,393 --> 00:24:40,312
(WHISPERING VOICES)

355
00:24:40,396 --> 00:24:43,899
FEMALE VOICE: Burn with the light.
Burn and turn!

356
00:24:51,740 --> 00:24:53,701
MAN: Now, boys, come along now.

357
00:24:54,535 --> 00:24:57,037
Classes are ready...

358
00:24:57,997 --> 00:24:59,873
Come along, Jenkins.

359
00:25:12,261 --> 00:25:15,264
BAINES: There is a trace,
but somehow scattered.

360
00:25:15,347 --> 00:25:17,266
The scent is confused.

361
00:25:18,100 --> 00:25:20,769
Nevertheless, we'd best arm ourselves.

362
00:25:21,937 --> 00:25:23,564
Activate the soldiers.

363
00:25:40,247 --> 00:25:44,460
That is my property!
And you are trespassing on my land!

364
00:25:45,210 --> 00:25:46,587
Come on, who's in there?

365
00:25:46,670 --> 00:25:49,214
Is it one of those idiot boys
from the school, is it? Eh?

366
00:25:49,298 --> 00:25:50,966
Come on. I suppose...

367
00:25:53,969 --> 00:25:55,637
Well, how did you...

368
00:25:59,475 --> 00:26:02,144
No! No! Help me!

369
00:26:02,728 --> 00:26:04,188
Help me!

370
00:26:18,160 --> 00:26:19,995
(SCREAMS)

371
00:26:25,876 --> 00:26:27,795
SMITH: Concentrate.

372
00:26:34,009 --> 00:26:36,178
Hutchinson, excellent work.

373
00:26:37,054 --> 00:26:40,182
-Cease fire!
-Good day to you, Headmaster.

374
00:26:40,265 --> 00:26:42,101
Your crew's on fine form today,
Mr Smith.

375
00:26:42,184 --> 00:26:44,311
Excuse me, Headmaster.
We could do a lot better.

376
00:26:44,394 --> 00:26:46,688
Latimer's being deliberately shoddy.

377
00:26:46,814 --> 00:26:49,233
-I'm trying my best.
-You need to be better than the best.

378
00:26:49,358 --> 00:26:52,069
Those targets are tribesmen
from the Dark Continent.

379
00:26:52,152 --> 00:26:55,614
That's exactly the problem, sir.
They only have spears.

380
00:26:55,697 --> 00:26:57,199
Oh, dear me.

381
00:26:57,282 --> 00:27:00,828
Latimer takes it upon himself
to make us realise how wrong we all are.

382
00:27:00,911 --> 00:27:02,538
I hope, Latimer, that one day

383
00:27:02,621 --> 00:27:06,208
you may have a just and proper war
in which to prove yourself.

384
00:27:06,333 --> 00:27:08,085
Now, resume firing.

385
00:27:12,381 --> 00:27:14,383
(BOMB WHISTLING)

386
00:27:15,592 --> 00:27:19,346
-Under the wire!
-Keep your heads down!

387
00:27:20,806 --> 00:27:24,393
One minute past the hour. It's now.

388
00:27:25,394 --> 00:27:27,938
Hutchinson, this is the time. It's now.

389
00:27:30,274 --> 00:27:32,526
Stoppage. Immediate action.

390
00:27:32,985 --> 00:27:35,612
Didn't I tell you, sir?
The stupid boy's useless.

391
00:27:35,737 --> 00:27:38,448
Permission to give Latimer
a beating, sir.

392
00:27:38,532 --> 00:27:40,951
-It's your class, Mr Smith.
-Permission granted.

393
00:27:41,034 --> 00:27:43,704
Right. Come with me, you little oik.

394
00:27:47,249 --> 00:27:48,917
(SNIFFS)

395
00:27:50,627 --> 00:27:52,671
Anything the matter, Baines?

396
00:27:52,754 --> 00:27:57,092
I thought... No, sir, nothing, sir.

397
00:28:00,512 --> 00:28:02,431
As you were, Mr Smith.

398
00:28:03,265 --> 00:28:07,060
Er, Pemberton, Smythe, Wicks, take post.

399
00:28:08,061 --> 00:28:09,146
Ah!

400
00:28:09,938 --> 00:28:11,565
Nurse Redfern.

401
00:28:11,648 --> 00:28:14,568
I'll give you back your journal
when next I see you.

402
00:28:14,651 --> 00:28:17,196
No, no, no, you don't have to.

403
00:28:17,279 --> 00:28:18,947
If you'll excuse me, Mr Smith,

404
00:28:19,031 --> 00:28:22,159
I was just thinking about the day
my husband was shot.

405
00:28:37,216 --> 00:28:40,886
His name was Oliver.
He died at the Battle of Spion Kop.

406
00:28:41,803 --> 00:28:44,139
We were childhood sweethearts.

407
00:28:45,307 --> 00:28:48,352
But, you see, I was angry
with the army for such a long time.

408
00:28:48,435 --> 00:28:50,395
And you still are.

409
00:28:50,479 --> 00:28:55,025
I find myself as part of that school,
watching boys learn how to kill.

410
00:28:55,108 --> 00:28:57,402
Don't you think discipline
is good for them?

411
00:28:57,486 --> 00:28:59,196
Does it have to be
such military discipline?

412
00:28:59,321 --> 00:29:02,241
If there's another war,
those boys won't find it so amusing.

413
00:29:02,324 --> 00:29:05,661
Well, Great Britain's at peace,
long may it reign.

414
00:29:07,329 --> 00:29:13,043
In your journal, in one of your stories,
you wrote about next year, 1914.

415
00:29:13,460 --> 00:29:15,128
It was just a dream.

416
00:29:15,212 --> 00:29:17,839
All those images of mud and wire.

417
00:29:18,632 --> 00:29:23,512
You told of a shadow. A shadow
falling across the entire world.

418
00:29:24,388 --> 00:29:27,391
Well, then, we can be thankful
it's not true.

419
00:29:27,474 --> 00:29:32,020
I'll admit, mankind doesn't need warfare
and bloodshed to prove itself.

420
00:29:32,145 --> 00:29:35,148
Everyday life can provide honour
and valour and...

421
00:29:35,232 --> 00:29:40,862
Let's hope that from now on this country
can find its heroes in smaller places.

422
00:29:45,659 --> 00:29:48,161
In the most

423
00:29:51,331 --> 00:29:53,375
ordinary of...

424
00:29:54,084 --> 00:29:55,877
Of deeds.

425
00:30:07,597 --> 00:30:09,182
(WOMAN SCREAMS)

426
00:30:20,736 --> 00:30:22,738
(BABY CRYING)

427
00:30:22,821 --> 00:30:24,531
Are you all right?

428
00:30:26,199 --> 00:30:29,411
-Lucky.
-That was luck?

429
00:30:30,287 --> 00:30:34,416
Miss Redfern, might I invite you
to the village dance this evening

430
00:30:34,499 --> 00:30:36,293
as my guest?

431
00:30:36,418 --> 00:30:38,962
You extraordinary man!

432
00:30:42,758 --> 00:30:47,095
Oh, it's all becoming clear now.
The Doctor is the man you'd like to be,

433
00:30:47,179 --> 00:30:49,306
doing impossible things
with cricket balls.

434
00:30:49,431 --> 00:30:51,933
Well, I discovered a talent,
that's certainly true.

435
00:30:52,017 --> 00:30:53,727
But the Doctor
has an eye for the ladies.

436
00:30:53,810 --> 00:30:56,146
-The devil!
-A girl at every fireplace.

437
00:30:56,229 --> 00:31:00,359
Ah! Now, there I have to protest, Joan.
That is hardly me.

438
00:31:00,942 --> 00:31:03,820
Says the man dancing with me tonight.

439
00:31:03,945 --> 00:31:06,073
That scarecrow's all askew.

440
00:31:11,620 --> 00:31:14,664
Ever the artist.
Where did you learn to draw?

441
00:31:14,790 --> 00:31:17,000
-Gallifrey.
-Is that in Ireland?

442
00:31:18,752 --> 00:31:21,171
-Yes, it must be.
-You're not Irish.

443
00:31:21,296 --> 00:31:25,926
Not at all, no. My father, Sidney,
was a watchmaker from Nottingham

444
00:31:26,968 --> 00:31:29,304
and my mother, Verity, was...

445
00:31:31,431 --> 00:31:33,642
-Well, she was a nurse, actually.
-Oh?

446
00:31:33,725 --> 00:31:37,104
-We make such good wives.
-Really? Right.

447
00:31:37,979 --> 00:31:39,314
Yes.

448
00:31:40,649 --> 00:31:42,692
Well, my work is done,
what do you think?

449
00:31:42,776 --> 00:31:44,569
Masterpiece.

450
00:31:44,653 --> 00:31:46,822
All sorts of skills today.

451
00:32:00,836 --> 00:32:02,421
Can I see?

452
00:32:08,176 --> 00:32:11,388
Oh, goodness. Do I look like that?

453
00:32:12,097 --> 00:32:13,849
Are you sure that's not me?

454
00:32:14,015 --> 00:32:16,601
No, it's certainly this page.
You like it?

455
00:32:16,726 --> 00:32:20,814
-You've made me far too beautiful.
-Well, that's how I see you.

456
00:32:22,357 --> 00:32:24,025
Widows aren't supposed to be beautiful.

457
00:32:24,109 --> 00:32:27,028
I think the world
would rather we stopped.

458
00:32:28,947 --> 00:32:30,574
Is that fair?

459
00:32:31,700 --> 00:32:33,201
That we stop?

460
00:32:35,412 --> 00:32:37,539
That's not fair at all.

461
00:32:55,098 --> 00:32:57,058
I've never, um...

462
00:33:04,316 --> 00:33:05,859
(DOOR OPENING)

463
00:33:06,234 --> 00:33:09,571
Martha, what have I told you
about entering unannounced?

464
00:33:12,324 --> 00:33:14,075
Wasn't on the list.

465
00:33:18,538 --> 00:33:20,749
(VIDEO FAST FORWARDING)

466
00:33:21,958 --> 00:33:25,504
Four, you. Don't let me abandon you.

467
00:33:26,338 --> 00:33:27,756
That's no good.

468
00:33:27,839 --> 00:33:31,092
What about the stuff you didn't tell me?
What about women?

469
00:33:31,301 --> 00:33:34,304
Oh, no, you didn't think of that.

470
00:33:34,387 --> 00:33:37,182
What the hell am I supposed to do, then?

471
00:33:37,265 --> 00:33:38,892
Thank you.

472
00:33:41,269 --> 00:33:43,355
You had to, didn't you?

473
00:33:44,105 --> 00:33:47,192
You had to go and
fall in love with a human.

474
00:33:48,068 --> 00:33:50,028
And it wasn't me.

475
00:33:51,988 --> 00:33:53,114
FEMALE VOICE: The darkness is coming.

476
00:33:53,198 --> 00:33:55,534
DOCTOR: Keep me away
from the false and empty man.

477
00:33:55,617 --> 00:34:00,997
MALE VOICE: The last of the Time Lords,
the last of that wise and ancient race.

478
00:34:01,081 --> 00:34:03,291
(VOICES MINGLING)

479
00:34:36,449 --> 00:34:40,787
Who's that playing silly beggars?
Nearly broke me neck.

480
00:34:40,870 --> 00:34:43,498
Who's that, then? Is that you, Saul?

481
00:34:53,883 --> 00:34:55,552
(JENNY WHIMPERING)

482
00:34:56,678 --> 00:34:58,305
I don't understand.

483
00:34:59,723 --> 00:35:01,725
It's Mr Clark, isn't it?

484
00:35:02,684 --> 00:35:05,061
What have I done wrong?

485
00:35:07,856 --> 00:35:10,108
Nothing at all.

486
00:35:10,191 --> 00:35:11,901
In fact,

487
00:35:12,986 --> 00:35:15,030
you're just what we need, girl.

488
00:35:15,113 --> 00:35:17,157
She works at the school.

489
00:35:18,491 --> 00:35:22,287
And whatever's happening seems to be
centred around that establishment.

490
00:35:22,370 --> 00:35:26,249
The faintest of traces,
but they all lead back there.

491
00:35:26,875 --> 00:35:28,585
It's Baines, isn't it?

492
00:35:30,045 --> 00:35:31,546
This isn't very funny, sir.

493
00:35:31,671 --> 00:35:35,425
Just shut up, stop talking,
cease and desist. There's a good girl!

494
00:35:36,217 --> 00:35:39,512
Mother of mine is dying to meet you.

495
00:35:41,723 --> 00:35:43,183
And here she is.

496
00:35:46,436 --> 00:35:49,105
-Stop mocking me, sir!
-No!

497
00:35:49,564 --> 00:35:52,942
Mother of mine just needs a shape.

498
00:35:53,068 --> 00:35:55,612
We go through shapes so very fast.

499
00:35:56,488 --> 00:35:58,740
Yours is perfectly adequate.

500
00:35:59,741 --> 00:36:01,534
If a little grim.

501
00:36:03,328 --> 00:36:04,913
Mother of mine,

502
00:36:05,914 --> 00:36:07,749
embrace her.

503
00:36:15,423 --> 00:36:17,258
You look wonderful.

504
00:36:17,342 --> 00:36:21,346
You'd best give me some warning.
Um... Can you actually dance?

505
00:36:22,764 --> 00:36:25,767
Um... I'm not certain.

506
00:36:26,726 --> 00:36:28,645
There's a surprise.

507
00:36:28,728 --> 00:36:31,189
Is there anything you're certain about?

508
00:36:31,272 --> 00:36:33,149
Yes. Yes.

509
00:36:38,613 --> 00:36:41,116
There you are. Come look what I've got.

510
00:36:41,199 --> 00:36:44,285
Mr Pool didn't want his afternoon tea,
so cook said I could have it.

511
00:36:44,452 --> 00:36:47,914
And there's enough for two.
What are you standing there for?

512
00:36:50,458 --> 00:36:53,795
-Are you all right?
-I must have a cold coming on.

513
00:36:55,130 --> 00:36:58,049
Problem is, I keep thinking about them,
but I don't know what to do.

514
00:36:58,133 --> 00:37:01,094
-Thinking about who?
-Mr Smith and Matron,

515
00:37:01,177 --> 00:37:04,764
'cause it's never gonna last,
he's gonna leave in a few weeks.

516
00:37:04,848 --> 00:37:06,141
Why?

517
00:37:06,224 --> 00:37:09,269
It's like his contract comes to an end
and she's going to be heartbroken.

518
00:37:09,352 --> 00:37:12,313
-Leave for where?
-All sorts of places.

519
00:37:12,981 --> 00:37:16,443
Oh, I wish I could tell you, Jenny,
but it's complicated.

520
00:37:16,526 --> 00:37:18,862
-In what way?
-I just can't.

521
00:37:19,904 --> 00:37:23,158
It sounds so interesting.
Tell me. Tell me now.

522
00:37:27,662 --> 00:37:30,290
-Would you like some tea?
-Yes, thanks.

523
00:37:30,373 --> 00:37:34,502
I could put a nice bit of gravy
in the pot and some mutton.

524
00:37:35,086 --> 00:37:37,505
Or sardines and jam, how about that?

525
00:37:38,381 --> 00:37:40,091
I like the sound of that.

526
00:37:40,216 --> 00:37:43,178
Right. Hold on a tick.

527
00:38:06,659 --> 00:38:08,369
-They've found us!
-This is ridiculous.

528
00:38:08,495 --> 00:38:11,080
-Martha, I've warned you.
-They've found us and I've seen them!

529
00:38:11,206 --> 00:38:13,333
They look like people, like us,
like normal.

530
00:38:13,416 --> 00:38:16,085
I'm sorry, but you've got
to open the watch.

531
00:38:18,171 --> 00:38:19,923
Where is it?

532
00:38:20,715 --> 00:38:22,509
Oh, my God! Where's it gone?
Where's the watch?

533
00:38:22,592 --> 00:38:23,718
What are you talking about?

534
00:38:23,843 --> 00:38:26,638
You had a watch,
a fob watch, right there.

535
00:38:26,721 --> 00:38:27,931
Did I? I don't remember.

536
00:38:28,056 --> 00:38:30,391
I can't think
what concern it is of yours.

537
00:38:30,517 --> 00:38:32,227
But we need it. Oh, my God, Doctor.

538
00:38:32,310 --> 00:38:34,854
We're hiding from aliens
and they've got Jenny

539
00:38:34,938 --> 00:38:37,565
and they've possessed her
or copied her or something,

540
00:38:37,690 --> 00:38:39,150
and you've got to tell me,
where's the watch?

541
00:38:39,234 --> 00:38:40,944
Oh, I see.

542
00:38:41,903 --> 00:38:43,738
Cultural differences.

543
00:38:45,114 --> 00:38:47,700
It must be so confusing for you.

544
00:38:47,784 --> 00:38:50,954
Martha, this is what we call a story.

545
00:38:51,913 --> 00:38:54,290
Oh, you complete...

546
00:38:54,415 --> 00:38:58,211
This is not you. This is 1913.

547
00:38:58,461 --> 00:39:00,296
Good. This is 1913.

548
00:39:00,380 --> 00:39:03,758
I'm sorry, I'm really sorry,
but I've got to snap you out of this.

549
00:39:03,883 --> 00:39:05,009
Martha!

550
00:39:05,093 --> 00:39:07,428
Wake up! You're coming back
to the Tardis with me.

551
00:39:07,512 --> 00:39:10,390
How dare you! I'm not going anywhere
with an insane servant.

552
00:39:10,473 --> 00:39:13,059
Martha, you are dismissed. You will
leave these premises immediately.

553
00:39:13,142 --> 00:39:14,853
Now, get out!

554
00:39:15,436 --> 00:39:17,897
The nerve of it! The absolute cheek!

555
00:39:17,981 --> 00:39:19,691
You think I'm a fantasist,
what about her?

556
00:39:19,774 --> 00:39:22,110
The funny thing is,
you did have a fob watch.

557
00:39:22,193 --> 00:39:24,612
Right there. Don't you remember?

558
00:39:28,199 --> 00:39:29,450
Oh! Sorry!

559
00:39:30,660 --> 00:39:32,161
Sorry!

560
00:39:32,287 --> 00:39:33,788
Martha?

561
00:39:33,913 --> 00:39:35,874
Not now, Tim, I'm busy!

562
00:39:49,971 --> 00:39:51,723
Mr Smith?

563
00:39:53,308 --> 00:39:54,767
No one home.

564
00:39:55,518 --> 00:39:58,187
The maid
was definitely hiding something.

565
00:39:58,271 --> 00:40:00,648
A secret around this Mr Smith.

566
00:40:00,773 --> 00:40:04,444
We both scented him, though,
he was plain and simply human.

567
00:40:04,527 --> 00:40:06,821
But maybe he knows something.

568
00:40:07,864 --> 00:40:09,532
Where is he?

569
00:40:10,992 --> 00:40:13,828
She's infatuated.
You're a dangerous man.

570
00:40:13,953 --> 00:40:16,998
-You've taken my arm in public.
-I'm very scared.

571
00:40:17,123 --> 00:40:19,792
Spare a penny
for the veterans of the Crimea, sir?

572
00:40:19,876 --> 00:40:23,087
Yes, of course. There you are, then.

573
00:40:34,682 --> 00:40:40,188
Ladies and gentlemen,
please take your partners for a waltz.

574
00:40:53,242 --> 00:40:56,245
-You can dance.
-Quite surprised myself.

575
00:40:57,455 --> 00:41:00,541
Oh, I say! Sorry.

576
00:41:10,218 --> 00:41:12,011
I think this might help.

577
00:41:14,222 --> 00:41:16,474
That makes it easy, Son of mine,

578
00:41:16,557 --> 00:41:19,102
because Daughter of mine's
already there.

579
00:41:19,227 --> 00:41:21,020
We've been invited to the dance.

580
00:41:28,069 --> 00:41:31,114
Oh, staff entrance I think, miss.

581
00:41:31,239 --> 00:41:33,282
Yeah, well, think again, mate.

582
00:41:51,217 --> 00:41:53,636
Please don't. Not again.

583
00:41:53,720 --> 00:41:57,265
He's different from any other man
you've ever met, right?

584
00:41:57,390 --> 00:41:58,516
Yes.

585
00:41:58,599 --> 00:42:01,019
And sometimes he says
these strange things,

586
00:42:01,102 --> 00:42:04,022
like people and places
you've never heard of, yeah?

587
00:42:04,105 --> 00:42:05,898
But it's deeper than that.

588
00:42:05,982 --> 00:42:08,776
Sometimes when
you look in his eyes, you know,

589
00:42:08,860 --> 00:42:12,071
you just know
that there's something else in there.

590
00:42:12,155 --> 00:42:13,865
Something hidden.

591
00:42:14,615 --> 00:42:17,243
Right behind the eyes,
something hidden away.

592
00:42:17,326 --> 00:42:20,580
-In the dark.
-I don't know what you mean.

593
00:42:21,372 --> 00:42:22,832
Yes, you do.

594
00:42:25,376 --> 00:42:27,295
I don't mean to be rude,

595
00:42:27,462 --> 00:42:31,049
but the awful thing is
it doesn't even matter what you think.

596
00:42:31,132 --> 00:42:33,801
But you're nice and you're lucky.

597
00:42:33,968 --> 00:42:36,721
And I just wanted to say sorry
for what I'm about to do.

598
00:42:36,804 --> 00:42:40,099
Oh, now, really, Martha,
this is getting out of hand.

599
00:42:40,183 --> 00:42:42,643
I must insist that you leave.

600
00:42:42,727 --> 00:42:44,437
Do you know what this is?

601
00:42:45,563 --> 00:42:46,939
Name it.

602
00:42:47,023 --> 00:42:48,983
Go on, name it.

603
00:42:49,734 --> 00:42:51,903
John, what is that silly thing?

604
00:42:51,986 --> 00:42:53,237
John?

605
00:43:01,829 --> 00:43:03,706
You're not John Smith.

606
00:43:04,540 --> 00:43:06,667
You're called the Doctor.

607
00:43:07,251 --> 00:43:09,837
The man in your journal, he's real.

608
00:43:10,463 --> 00:43:11,798
He's you.

609
00:43:14,217 --> 00:43:17,220
Evening, all! Spare a penny, sir?

610
00:43:17,512 --> 00:43:19,305
I didn't spare you.

611
00:43:40,701 --> 00:43:43,830
You will be silent!

612
00:43:44,330 --> 00:43:46,165
All of you!

613
00:43:46,582 --> 00:43:48,543
I said, silent!

614
00:43:48,626 --> 00:43:51,129
Mr Clark, what's going on?

615
00:43:55,883 --> 00:43:58,261
Mr Smith, everything I told you,
just forget it.

616
00:43:58,344 --> 00:43:59,512
Don't say anything.

617
00:43:59,595 --> 00:44:01,889
We asked for silence!

618
00:44:04,600 --> 00:44:06,018
Now then,

619
00:44:06,936 --> 00:44:09,981
we have a few questions for Mr Smith.

620
00:44:10,064 --> 00:44:13,109
No, better than that.

621
00:44:13,192 --> 00:44:15,528
The teacher, he's the Doctor.

622
00:44:16,195 --> 00:44:17,989
I heard them talking.

623
00:44:18,072 --> 00:44:20,283
You took human form.

624
00:44:20,366 --> 00:44:23,452
Of course I'm human!
I was born human, as were you, Baines!

625
00:44:23,536 --> 00:44:25,663
And Jenny and you, Mr Clark.

626
00:44:25,746 --> 00:44:28,332
What is going on? This is madness!

627
00:44:28,416 --> 00:44:32,837
Ooh, and a human brain, too.
Simple, thick and dull.

628
00:44:33,171 --> 00:44:35,339
But he's no good like this.

629
00:44:35,423 --> 00:44:37,633
We need a Time Lord.

630
00:44:37,758 --> 00:44:39,218
Easily done.

631
00:44:41,596 --> 00:44:43,139
(ALL GASP)

632
00:44:43,764 --> 00:44:45,975
-Change back.
-I don't know what you're talking about.

633
00:44:46,100 --> 00:44:47,435
Change back!

634
00:44:47,560 --> 00:44:50,146
I literally do not know...

635
00:44:50,438 --> 00:44:53,316
-Get off me!
-She's your friend, isn't she?

636
00:44:53,441 --> 00:44:55,943
Doesn't this scare you enough
to change back?

637
00:44:56,027 --> 00:44:59,197
-I don't know what you mean!
-Wait a minute.

638
00:44:59,280 --> 00:45:02,992
The maid told me about
Smith and the matron.

639
00:45:03,117 --> 00:45:05,661
-That woman, there.
-Then let's have you!

640
00:45:09,790 --> 00:45:12,668
Have you enjoyed it, Doctor?
Being human?

641
00:45:12,793 --> 00:45:17,006
Has it taught you wonderful things?
Are you better, richer, wiser?

642
00:45:17,673 --> 00:45:20,092
Then let's see you answer this.

643
00:45:20,176 --> 00:45:23,054
Which one of them
do you want us to kill?

644
00:45:24,388 --> 00:45:26,015
Maid or matron?

645
00:45:26,807 --> 00:45:28,643
Your friend

646
00:45:28,726 --> 00:45:30,394
or your lover?

647
00:45:31,145 --> 00:45:32,813
Your choice.

648
00:46:29,370 --> 00:46:31,205
We are the Family of Blood.

649
00:46:31,706 --> 00:46:33,416
(CHURCH BELLS RINGING)

650
00:46:39,422 --> 00:46:40,798
Save us.

651
00:46:40,881 --> 00:46:42,633
I am not the Doctor.

652
00:46:42,717 --> 00:46:45,845
TIM: He's like the night
and the storm and the heart of the sun.

653
00:46:45,928 --> 00:46:47,263
He's ancient and forever.

654
00:46:47,388 --> 00:46:50,850
He burns at the centre of time
and he can see the turn of the universe.

